description:
## Background

`checkIcicleLandings()` (~line 605) uses `[weak self]` inside its `enumerateChildNodes` closure. The sibling `integrateCustomGravity()` (~line 592) does NOT. Both are called from the same `update(_:)` loop, on the same `GameScene` instance. Neither closure escapes (`enumerateChildNodes` invokes the block synchronously and doesn't retain it), so neither version leaks. The inconsistency is a code smell, not a bug.

## Fix

Add `[weak self]` to `integrateCustomGravity` for symmetry. Inside, `guard let self else { return }` early so the rest of the block can use `self.iceTopY` etc. unguarded.

```swift
private func integrateCustomGravity(dt: TimeInterval) {
    for name in ["icicle", "shard"] {
        enumerateChildNodes(withName: name) { [weak self] node, _ in
            guard self != nil,
                  let g = node.userData?["gravity"] as? CGFloat,
                  let body = node.physicsBody else { return }
            body.velocity.dy -= g * CGFloat(dt)
        }
    }
}
```

(The current method doesn't actually USE self inside the block — it only accesses dt, node, and body. So adding `[weak self]` is defensive symmetry rather than a functional change. Alternatively, REMOVE `[weak self]` from `checkIcicleLandings` since `enumerateChildNodes` provably doesn't escape — but `checkIcicleLandings` does access `self.iceTopY` and other self properties, so it benefits from explicit weak self.)

## Acceptance

Both methods use the same capture style. No behavior change.

## Files

PenguinSlide/GameScene.swift (or IcicleSystem.swift after Bead #6).
